<subSubSection pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[172,434,2102,2127]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 75-113 mm, tail 85-135 mm, ear 17-23 mm, hindfoot 21-25 mm; weight 25-27 g. Dorsum of Olrog’s Chaco Mouse is yellowish brown to light brownish olive, with small whitish subauricular and post-auricular patches; venter and upper surfaces of forefeet and hindfeet are white. Tail terminates in moderate tuft, with hairs extending c¢.5 mm beyond tip. Females have three pairs of mammae, based on one female. Chromosomal complement is 2n = 60, FN = 116.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,282,2369,2402]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">Habitat.</emphasis>
Arid and semiarid habitats associated to Chaco and Monte biomes. Olrog’s Chaco Mouseis found in low thornscrub bordering salt flats and in disturbed Chacoan thornscrub. Type series was trapped in or near stands of creosote bush (
<taxonomicName box="[1197,1285,2448,2481]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Larrea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="252" pageNumber="530" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Larrea</taxonomicName>
tridentata, 
<taxonomicName box="[242,459,2488,2521]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="252" pageNumber="530" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Zygophyllaceae</taxonomicName>
) on fine-textured soils on the floor of the Bolson de Pipanaco, Catamarca.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[171,670,2565,2598]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" box="[171,670,2565,2598]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,432,2565,2598]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,305,2606,2639]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">Breeding.</emphasis>
Male Olrog’s Chaco Mice with scrotal testes and one pregnant female that gave birth to five young were recorded in May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[169,1109,2684,2717]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" box="[169,1109,2684,2717]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[169,404,2684,2717]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Olrog’s Chaco Mouse is nocturnal and terrestrial.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[170,1109,2723,2756]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="252.[169,1377,1934,2874]" box="[170,1109,2723,2756]" pageId="252" pageNumber="530">
